            "creation_date": 1292414071,
            "body": "<p>If it is a numeric field in the database, it is not storing it as <code>21,2500<\/code>.  Instead - it is storing it as <code>21.25<\/code>, but the interface that you are using is formatting it for you.  In this case it is showing you 4 digits after the decimal and putting a <code>,<\/code> in for the decimal separator.  I suggest that you do just what your database interface is doing, format the data the way you need it.  <\/p>\n\n<p>See the <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/text/DecimalFormat.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">JavaDoc for DecimalFormat<\/a> and the <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/i18n/format/decimalFormat.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Java tutorial on custom formats<\/a> for some details.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 4449598,
            "question_id": 4449498
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53ee9941b3fefef67175daf212e62d41?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
